# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: centrifugal-compressor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Born in Lübeck, Germany, Busemann attended the Technical University of Braunschweig, receiving his Ph.D. in engineering in 1924.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] The next year he was given the position of aeronautical research scientist at the Max-Planck Institute where he joined the famed team led by Ludwig Prandtl, including Theodore von Kármán, Max Munk and Jakob Ackeret.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] In 1930 he was promoted to professor at University of Göttingen.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] He held various positions within the German scientific community during this period, and during the war he was the director of the Braunschweig Laboratory, a famous research establishment.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Busemann discovered the benefits of the swept wing for aircraft at high speeds, presenting a paper on the topic at the Fifth Volta Conference in Rome on October 3, 1935, the very day of Italian invasion of Ethiopia which caused a delay of his talk.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] The paper concerned only supersonic lift.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Nevertheless, he continued working with the concept, and by the end of the year had demonstrated similar benefits in the transonic region as well, after which the research topic was classified.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] As director of the Braunschweig labs, he started an experimental wind tunnel test series of the concept, and by 1942 had amassed a considerable amount of useful technical data.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] As the need for higher speed aircraft became pressing in Germany, the Messerschmitt Me P.1101 was developed to flight test these designs.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] When World War II ended, a team of American aerodynamicists travelled to Germany as part of Operation Lusty.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] The team included Theodore von Kármán, Tsien Hsue-shen, Hugh Dryden and George S.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] They reached the Braunschweig labs on 7 May, where they found a mass of data on the swept wing concept.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] When they asked Busemann about it, "his face lit up" and he said, "Oh, you remember, I read a paper on it at the Volta Conference in 1935".
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Several members of the team did remember the presentation, but had completely forgotten the details in terms of what the presentation was actually about.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Realizing its importance, Schairer immediately wrote to Boeing and told them to investigate the concept, leading to a re-modeling of the B-47 Stratojet with a swept wing.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Busemann's work, along with similar work by Robert T.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Jones in the US, led to a revolution in aircraft design.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Near the end of the war, Busemann started studying airflow around delta wings, leading to the development of his supersonic conical flow theory.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] This reduced the complexity of the airflow to a conformal mapping in the complex plane, and was used for some time in the industry.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Busemann moved to the United States in 1947 and started work at NACA's Langley Research Center.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] In 1951 he gave a talk where he described the fact that air at near supersonic speeds no longer varied in diameter with speed according to Bernoulli's theorem but remained largely incompressible and acting as fixed diameter pipes, or as he put it, 'streampipes'.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] He jokingly referred to aerodynamicists as needing to become 'pipe fitters'.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] This talk led an attendee, Richard Whitcomb, to try and work out what these pipes were doing in a transonic test he was performing, inventing the Whitcomb area rule a few days later.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] At Langley, he worked primarily on the problems of sonic booms, and spent a considerable amount of effort looking at ways to characterize them, and potentially eliminate them.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] He later invented Busemann's Biplane, a supersonic design he originally proposed in 1936 that emits no shock waves and has no wave drag, albeit at the cost of having no lift.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Busemann also did early work on magneto-hydrodynamics in the 1920s, as well as on cylindrical focusing of shock waves and non-steady gas dynamics.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] Busemann held a professorship at the University of Colorado from 1963 and suggested the use of ceramic tiles on the Space Shuttle, which were adopted by NASA.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/adolf-busemann] He was awarded the Ludwig-Prandtl-Ring from the Deutsche Gesellschaft für Luft- und Raumfahrt (German Society for Aeronautics and Astronautics) for "outstanding contribution in the field of aerospace engineering" in 1966.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] The **ASHRAE Handbook** is the four-volume flagship publication of the nonprofit technical organization **ASHRAE** (**American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers**).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] This Handbook is considered the most comprehensive and authoritative repository of practical knowledge on the various topics that form the field of heating, ventilation, air-conditioning, and refrigeration (HVAC&R).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] The four volumes are *Fundamentals*, *Refrigeration*, *HVAC Applications* ("Applications"), and *HVAC Systems and Equipment* ("Systems and Equipment").
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] Members of ASHRAE receive the current volume, in both print and CD-ROM form, each year as a basic membership benefit.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] An enhanced electronic version, known as *ASHRAE Handbook Online* is a web-based version updated annually that contains the four latest volumes as well as extra content such as calculations, demonstration videos, and spreadsheets.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] The various versions of the Handbook are typically available to the public via technical, and other, libraries and bookstores.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] The ASHRAE Handbook has had a variety of titles.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] It began in 1922 as the **ASH&VE Guide**.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] In 1973 it became the ASHRAE Handbook, and in 1985 separate publication of inch-pound (I-P) and international system (SI) units versions of the volumes began.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] Stephen Comstock, and the Editor is Mark S.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook is published by ASHRAE from its headquarters in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] The Handbook's content is created and modified by volunteers via ASHRAE's many Technical Committees (TCs), and then edited and formatted by professional staff at ASHRAE.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] For example, three chapters, in three different volumes, are maintained by TC 5.3, Room Air Distribution.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] Each chapter within a particular volume is reviewed and revised in a repeating four-year cycle; one volume is printed each year.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] In the summer of 2017 the new Fundamentals' volume was released.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] ASHRAE's Handbook Committee maintains an *Authors and Revisers Guide,* which can be obtained freely via the Handbook portion of the ASHRAE Web site.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] While each new or revised chapter manuscript is to be reviewed for technical content by each TC voting and corresponding member before publication, there are often many other pre- and post-publication reviewers.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] For example, members of the Society's Handbook Committee and the College of Fellows review chapters each year.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae-handbook] Reviews, from basic comments to detailed new content, are encouraged from all users of the Handbook and may be submitted through an online commenting system.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] The **American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers** (**ASHRAE** /ˈæʃreɪ/ *ASH-ray*) is an American professional association seeking to advance heating, ventilation, air conditioning and refrigeration (HVAC&R) systems design and construction.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] ASHRAE has over 50,000 members in more than 130 countries worldwide.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] ASHRAE's members comprise building services engineers, architects, mechanical contractors, building owners, equipment manufacturers' employees, and others concerned with the design and construction of HVAC&R systems in buildings.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] The society funds research projects, offers continuing education programs, and develops and publishes technical standards to improve building services engineering, energy efficiency, indoor air quality, and sustainable development.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] ASHRAE was founded in 1894 at a meeting of engineers in New York City, formerly headquartered at 345 East 47th Street (the United Engineering Center), and has held an annual meeting since 1895.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] Until 1954 it was known as the American Society of Heating and Ventilating Engineers (ASHVE); in that year it changed its name to the American Society of Heating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHAE).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] Its current name and organization came from the 1959 merger of ASHAE and the American Society of Refrigerating Engineers (ASRE).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] Despite having 'American' in its name, ASHRAE is a global organization, holding international events.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] In 2012, it rebranded itself with a new logo and tagline: "Shaping Tomorrow's Built Environment Today".
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] The ASHRAE Handbook is a four-volume resource for HVAC&R technology and is available in both print and electronic versions.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] The volumes are *Fundamentals*, *HVAC Applications*, *HVAC Systems and Equipment*, and *Refrigeration*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] One of the four volumes is updated each year.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes a set of standards and guidelines relating to HVAC systems and issues, that are often referenced in building codes and used by consulting engineers, mechanical contractors, architects, and government agencies.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] These standards are periodically reviewed, revised and republished.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] The society also publishes two magazines: the *ASHRAE Journal* is issued monthly, and *High Performing Buildings Magazine* is published quarterly.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] They contain articles on related technology, information on upcoming meetings, editorials, and case studies of various well-performing buildings.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] ASHRAE also publishes books, *ASHRAE Transactions*, and the *International Journal of HVAC&R Research*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] ASHRAE supported the Streamlining Energy Efficiency for Schools Act of 2014 (H.R.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] 4092; 113th Congress), a bill that would require the United States Department of Energy to establish a centralized clearinghouse to disseminate information on federal programs, incentives, and mechanisms for financing energy-efficient retrofits and upgrades at schools.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] ASHRAE offers six categories of awards: achievement awards to recognize personal honors; personal awards for general and specific society activities; paper awards; society awards for groups or chapters; chapters and regional awards.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] ASHRAE Fellow is a Membership Grade of Distinction conferred by The College of Fellows of ASHRAE, Inc. to an ASHRAE member with significant publications or innovations and distinguished scientific and engineering background in the fields of heating, refrigeration, air conditioning, ventilation.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] The ASHRAE Fellow membership grade is the highest elected grade in ASHRAE.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] ASHRAE has a Hall of Fame honoring "deceased members who have made milestone contributions to the growth of ASHRAE-related technology.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] To demonstrate the Society's commitment to sustainability, ASHRAE renovated its previous headquarters building in Atlanta, Ga.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] After the renovation and occupancy in June 2008, the building received many awards, including an Energy Star rating with a score of 95, a Platinum Certification from USGBC's LEED program, and four Green Globes from the Green Building Initiative.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] The current site energy use intensity (EUI) is 35.8 kBtu/Sqft (411 MJ/m2), a 60 percent reduction from the pre-renovation value.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] The renovation included the use of a dedicated outdoor air supply (DOAS) system with energy recovery and humidity control; a ground-source heat pump system; and variable refrigerant flow systems with heat recovery.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] The building also serves as a live case study.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] A web-based user interface allowed researchers around the world to extract data from the building to study factors such as energy use and electric power demand, water consumption and indoor air quality.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] In 2018, ASHRAE decided to move their world headquarters, settling on retrofitting a 1970s-era building in Peachtree Corners, suburban Atlanta.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/ashrae] Completed in 2022, the building has been renovated to comply with ASHRAE's own standards, including ASHRAE 90.1, and the organization has the goal of operating the building at net-zero energy, powered by a large on-site solar array.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The **ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC)** is a set of standards published by the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) that provides rules for the design, fabrication, inspection, testing, and certification of boilers and pressure vessels.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The BPVC is developed and updated through a consensus process managed by ASME committees, with participation from volunteer technical experts representing industry, regulators, and other stakeholders.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] ASME also operates a conformity assessment and certification system under which accredited organizations—including manufacturers and authorized inspection agencies—may apply ASME Code Symbol Stamps to equipment that meets BPVC requirements.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The BPVC was created in response to public outcry after several serious explosions in the state of Massachusetts.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] A fire-tube boiler exploded at the Grover Shoe Factory in Brockton, Massachusetts, on March 20, 1905, which resulted in the deaths of 58 people and injured 150.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Then on December 6, 1906, a boiler in the factory of the P.J.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Harney Shoe Company exploded in Lynn, Massachusetts.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] As a result, the state of Massachusetts enacted the first legal code based on ASME's rules for the construction of steam boilers in 1907.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] ASME convened the Board of Boiler Rules before it became the ASME Boiler Code Committee which was formed in 1911.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] This committee put in the form work for the first edition of the ASME Boiler Code - Rules for the Construction of Stationary Boilers and for the Allowable Working Pressures, which was issued in 1914 and published in 1915.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The first edition of the Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code, known as the 1914 edition, was a single 114-page volume.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It developed over time into the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel code, which today has over 92,000 copies in use, in over 100 countries around the world.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] As of March 2011 the document consisted of 16,000 pages in 28 volumes.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] After the first edition of the Code, the verifications required by the Code were performed by independent inspectors, which resulted in a wide range of interpretations.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Hence in February 1919, the National Board of Boiler and Pressure Vessel Inspectors was formed.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Addenda, which include additions and revisions to the individual Sections of the Code, are issued accordingly for a particular edition of the code up until the next edition.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Addenda is no longer in use since Code Edition 2013.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It has been replaced by two years edition period.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] ASME's interpretations to submitted technical queries relevant to a particular Section of the Code are issued accordingly.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Interpretations are also available through the internet.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Code Cases provide rules that permit the use of materials and alternative methods of construction that are not covered by existing BPVC rules.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Codes Cases are usually intended to be incorporated in the Code in a later edition.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] When it is used, the Code Case specifies mandatory requirements which must be met as it would be with the Code.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] There are some jurisdictions that do not automatically accept Code Cases.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The section of the ASME BPVC consists of 4 parts.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] This Part is a supplementary book referenced by other sections of the Code.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It provides material specifications for ferrous materials which are suitable for use in the construction of pressure vessels.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The specifications contained in this Part specify the mechanical properties, heat treatment, heat and product chemical composition and analysis, test specimens, and methodologies of testing.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The designation of the specifications start with 'SA' and a number which is taken from the ASTM 'A' specifications.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It provides material specifications for nonferrous materials which are suitable for use in the construction of pressure vessels.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The designation of the specifications start with 'SB' and a number which is taken from the ASTM 'B' specifications.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It provides mechanical properties, heat treatment, heat and product chemical composition and analysis, test specimens, and methodologies of testing for welding rods, filler metals and electrodes used in the construction of pressure vessels.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The specifications contained in this Part are designated with 'SFA' and a number which is taken from the American Welding Society (AWS) specifications.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Section III of the ASME Code Address the rules for construction of nuclear facility components and supports.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The components and supports covered by section III are intended to be installed in a nuclear power system that serves the purpose of producing and controlling the output of thermal energy from nuclear fuel and those associated systems essential to safety of nuclear power system.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Section III provides requirements for new construction of nuclear power system considering mechanical and thermal stresses due to cyclic operation.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Deterioration, which may occur in service as result of radiation effects, corrosion, or instability of the material, is typically not addressed.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] This section of the ASME BPVC contains the requirements for nondestructive examinations which are referred and required by other sections of the Code.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] It also covers the suppliers examination responsibilities, requirements of the authorized inspectors (AI) as well as the requirements for the qualification of personnel, inspection and examinations.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] This section of the ASME BPVC consists of 3 divisions.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] 1 covers the mandatory requirements, specific prohibitions and nonmandatory guidance for materials, design, fabrication, inspection and testing, markings and reports, overpressure protection and certification of pressure vessels having an internal or external pressure which exceeds 15 psi (100 kPa).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Pressure vessels covered by this division can be either fired or unfired.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure may be from external sources, or by the application of heating from an indirect or direct source, or any combination thereof.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The division is not numbered in the traditional method (Part 1, Part 2 etc.) but is structured with Subsections and Parts which consist of letters followed by a number.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure vessels can be either fired or unfired.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure may be from external sources, or by the application of heating from an indirect or direct source as a result of a process, or any combination of the two.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The rules contained in this section can be used as an alternative to the minimum requirements specified in Division 1.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Generally the Division 2 rules are more onerous than in Division 1 with respect to materials, design and nondestructive examinations but higher design stress intensity values are allowed.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Division 2 has also provisions for the use of finite element analysis to determine expected stress in pressure equipment, in addition to the traditional approach of *design by formula* (Part 5: "Design by Analysis requirements").
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure vessel can be either fired or unfired.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The pressure may be from external sources, by the application of heating from an indirect or direct source, process reaction or any combination thereof.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Prior to the introduction of Section IX, individual sections of the BPVC contained their own separate and varying qualification requirements for welded construction.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Section IX was first published as a standalone section of the BPVC in 1941, initially covering only three welding processes: Shielded Metal Arc Welding (SMAW), Oxy-Fuel Welding (OFW), and Carbon-Arc Welding (CAW).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The fundamental philosophy of qualifying procedures and personnel while permitting qualified ranges of variables has remained largely unchanged since this first edition.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Although additional joining processes and qualification rules have been incorporated over time to keep pace with industrial technology, the core mechanics of the code have remained highly stable.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The scope of Section IX has expanded periodically over its history.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Brazing qualifications were incorporated in the 1960 edition, turning it into the "Welding and Brazing Qualifications" standard.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] The 2013 edition introduced qualification requirements for plastic fusing, along with a common set of general requirements applicable to all material-joining processes.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] For welding, Section IX establishes requirements for qualifying Welding Procedure Specifications (WPSs) by means of Procedure Qualification Records (PQRs) and for qualifying welders and welding operators through performance qualification tests.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Similar qualification systems are provided for brazing procedures and brazers, and for plastic fusing procedures and operators.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] To reduce the administrative and economic burden of procedure qualifications, Section IX groups base materials into P-Numbers and welding filler metals into F-Numbers.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Qualification of a procedure using one material or filler metal may therefore extend to other materials or filler metals within the same classification, subject to the qualification rules of the Code.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Section IX is referenced by numerous ASME construction codes, including those governing boilers, pressure vessels, and pressure piping.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Because of its rigorous framework and historical reliability, it is widely used internationally as the definitive qualification standard for joining procedures and personnel in pressure equipment fabrication, even in countries that do not otherwise utilize the ASME construction codes.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme-boiler-and-pressure-vessel-code] Within ISO-based manufacturing systems, it serves a functionally parallel purpose to the ISO 15614 series (for procedure qualification) and the ISO 9606 series (for personnel qualification).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/asme] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] They achieve pressure rise by adding energy to the continuous flow of fluid through the rotor/impeller.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The equation in the next section shows this specific energy input.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] A substantial portion of this energy is kinetic, which is converted to increased potential energy/static pressure by slowing the flow through a diffuser.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The static pressure rise in the impeller may roughly equal the rise in the diffuser.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] A simple centrifugal compressor stage has four components (listed in order of throughflow): inlet, impeller/rotor, diffuser, and collector.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Figure 1.1 shows each of the components of the flow path, with the flow (working gas) entering the centrifugal impeller axially from left to right.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This turboshaft (or turboprop) impeller is rotating counter-clockwise when looking downstream into the compressor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The flow will pass through the compressors from left to right.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The simplest inlet to a centrifugal compressor is typically a simple pipe.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Depending upon its use/application, inlets can be very complex.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] They may include other components such as an inlet throttle valve, a shrouded port, an annular duct (see Figure 1.1), a bifurcated duct, stationary guide vanes/airfoils used to straight or swirl flow (see Figure 1.1), movable guide vanes (used to vary pre-swirl adjustably).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Compressor inlets often include instrumentation to measure pressure and temperature in order to control compressor performance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Bernoulli's principle plays an important role in understanding vaneless stationary components like an inlet.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The identifying component of a centrifugal compressor stage is the centrifugal impeller rotor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Impellers are designed in many configurations including "open" (visible blades), "covered or shrouded", "with splitters" (every other inducer removed), and "without splitters" (all full blades).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Figures 1.1, 1.2.1, and 1.3 show three different open, full-inducer rotors with alternating full blades/vanes and shorter-length splitter blades/vanes.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Generally, the accepted mathematical nomenclature refers to the leading edge of the impeller with subscript 1.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Correspondingly, the trailing edge of the impeller is referred to as subscript 2.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] As the working-gas/flow passes through the impeller from stations 1 to 2, the kinetic and potential energy increase.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This is identical to an axial compressor with the exception that the gases can reach higher energy levels through the impeller's increasing radius.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In many modern high-efficiency centrifugal compressors, the gas exiting the impeller is traveling near the speed of sound.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Most modern high-efficiency impellers use "backsweep" in the blade shape.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Derived from the general Euler equations is Euler's pump and turbine equation, which plays an important role in understanding impeller performance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The next component downstream of the impeller within a simple centrifugal compressor may be the diffuser.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The diffuser converts the flow's kinetic energy (high velocity) into increased potential energy (static pressure) by gradually slowing (diffusing) the gas velocity.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Diffusers can be vaneless, vaned, or an alternating combination.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] High-efficiency vaned diffusers are also designed over a wide range of solidities from less than 1 to over 4.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Hybrid versions of vaned diffusers include wedge (see Figure 1.3), channel, and pipe diffusers.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Generally accepted nomenclature might refer to the diffuser's leading edge as station 3 and the trailing edge as station 4.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Bernoulli's principle plays an important role in understanding diffuser performance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The collector of a centrifugal compressor can take many shapes and forms.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] When the diffuser discharges into a large, empty, circumferentially constant-area chamber, the collector may be termed a *Plenum*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] When the diffuser discharges into a device that looks somewhat like a snail shell, bull's horn, or a French horn, the collector is likely to be termed a *volute* or *scroll*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] When the diffuser discharges into an annular bend, the collector may be referred to as a *combustor inlet* (as used in jet engines or gas turbines) or a *return channel* (as used in an online multi-stage compressor).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] As the name implies, a collector's purpose is to gather the flow from the diffuser discharge annulus and deliver this flow downstream into whatever component the application requires.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The collector or discharge pipe may also contain valves and instrumentation to control the compressor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In some applications, collectors will diffuse flow (converting kinetic energy to static pressure) far less efficiently than a diffuser.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Over the past 100 years, applied scientists including Stodola (1903, 1927–1945), Pfleiderer (1952), Hawthorne (1964), Shepherd (1956), Lakshminarayana (1996), and Japikse (many texts including citations), have educated young engineers in the fundamentals of turbomachinery.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] These understandings apply to all dynamic, continuous-flow, axisymmetric pumps, fans, blowers, and compressors in axial, mixed-flow, and radial/centrifugal configurations.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This relationship is the reason advances in turbines and axial compressors often find their way into other turbomachinery, including centrifugal compressors.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Figures 2.1 and 2.2 illustrate the domain of turbomachinery with labels showing centrifugal compressors.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Improvements in centrifugal compressors have not been achieved through large discoveries.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Rather, improvements have been achieved through understanding and applying incremental pieces of knowledge discovered by many individuals.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Figure 2.1 (shown right) represents the aero-thermo domain of turbomachinery.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The horizontal axis represents the energy equation derivable from the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The vertical axis, which can be characterized by Mach number, represents the range of fluid compressibility (or elasticity).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The Z-axis, which can be characterized by Reynolds number, represents the range of fluid viscosities (or stickiness).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Figure 2.2 (shown right) represents the physical or mechanical domain of turbomachinery.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Again, the horizontal axis represents the energy equation with turbines generating power to the left and compressors absorbing power to the right.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Within the physical domain the vertical axis differentiates between high speeds and low speeds depending upon the turbomachinery application.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The Z-axis differentiates between axial-flow geometry and radial-flow geometry within the physical domain of turbomachinery.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] It is implied that mixed-flow turbomachinery lie between axial and radial.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Key contributors of technical achievements that pushed the practical application of turbomachinery forward include Denis Papin, Kernelien Le Demour, Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit, John Smeaton, Dr.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Rateau, John Barber, Alexander Sablukov, Sir Charles Algernon Parsons, Ægidius Elling, Sanford Alexander Moss, Willis Carrier, Adolf Busemann, Hermann Schlichting, Frank Whittle, and Hans von Ohain.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Centrifugal compressors are similar to axial compressors in that they are rotating airfoil-based compressors.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Both are shown in the adjacent photograph of an engine with 5 stages of axial compressors and one stage of a centrifugal compressor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The first part of the centrifugal impeller looks very similar to an axial compressor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This first part of the centrifugal impeller is also termed an *inducer*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Centrifugal compressors differ from axials as they use a significant change in radius from inlet to exit of the impeller to produce a much greater pressure rise in a single stage (e.g.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] 8 in the Pratt & Whitney Canada PW200 series of helicopter engines) than does an axial stage.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The 1940s-era German Heinkel HeS 011 experimental engine was the first aviation turbojet to have a compressor stage with radial flow-turning part-way between none for an axial and 90 degrees for a centrifugal.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] It is known as a mixed/diagonal-flow compressor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] A diagonal stage is used in the Pratt & Whitney Canada PW600 series of small turbofans.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Centrifugal compressors are also similar to centrifugal fans of the style shown in the neighboring figure, as they both increase the energy of the flow through the increasing radius.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In contrast to centrifugal fans, compressors operate at higher speeds to generate greater pressure rises.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In many cases, the engineering methods used to design a centrifugal fan are the same as those to design a centrifugal compressor, so they can look very similar.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] For purposes of generalization and definition, it can be said that centrifugal compressors often have density increases greater than 5 percent.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Also, they often experience relative fluid velocities above Mach number 0.3 when the working fluid is air or nitrogen.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In contrast, fans or blowers are often considered to have density increases of less than five percent and peak relative fluid velocities below Mach 0.3.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Squirrel-cage fans are primarily used for ventilation.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The flow field within this type of fan has internal recirculations.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In comparison, a centrifugal fan is uniform circumferentially.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Centrifugal compressors are also similar to centrifugal pumps of the style shown in the adjacent figures.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The key difference between such compressors and pumps is that the compressor working fluid is a gas (compressible) and the pump working fluid is liquid (incompressible).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Again, the engineering methods used to design a centrifugal pump are the same as those to design a centrifugal compressor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Yet, there is one important difference: the need to deal with cavitation in pumps.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Although centrifugal compressors and centrifugal pumps share similar mechanical layouts, their design objectives differ due to the compressibility of the working fluid.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In centrifugal compressors, changes in gas density and temperature during compression significantly influence impeller design, diffuser geometry, and overall stage performance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In contrast, centrifugal pumps primarily operate with incompressible liquids, allowing density to be treated as constant during operation.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] As a result, compressors require additional considerations such as surge control, choke limits, and thermal effects, which are generally not critical in pump design.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In centrifugal compressors, energy is transferred to the gas primarily through the rotating impeller, increasing both velocity and pressure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The high-velocity gas then passes through a diffuser, where a portion of the kinetic energy is converted into static pressure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This process is similar in principle to centrifugal pumps, although the effects of compressibility are significant only in compressors.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Because gases are compressible, centrifugal compressors experience changes in density throughout the flow path, which affects pressure rise and efficiency.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Pump operation, using incompressible liquids, does not involve such density variations, simplifying performance prediction and control.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Centrifugal compressors also look very similar to their turbomachinery counterpart, the radial turbine, as shown in the figure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] While a compressor transfers energy into a flow to raise its pressure, a turbine operates in reverse, by extracting energy from a flow, thus reducing its pressure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In other words, power is input to compressors and output from turbines.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] As turbomachinery has become more common, standards have been created to guide manufacturers to assure end-users that their products meet minimum safety and performance requirements.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Associations formed to codify these standards rely on manufacturers, end-users, and related technical specialists.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Below is a partial list of centrifugal-compressor applications, each with a brief description of some of the general characteristics possessed by those compressors.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] To start this list, two of the most well-known centrifugal compressor applications are listed: gas turbines and turbochargers.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In the case where flow passes through a straight pipe to enter a centrifugal compressor, the flow is axial, uniform, and has no vorticity, i.e. swirling motion.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] As the flow passes through the centrifugal impeller, the impeller forces the flow to spin faster as it gets further from the rotational axis.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] According to Euler's *pump and turbine equation*, the energy input to the fluid is proportional to the flow's local spinning velocity multiplied by the local impeller tangential velocity.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In many cases, the flow leaving the centrifugal impeller is traveling near the speed of sound.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] It then flows through a stationary compressor causing it to decelerate.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The stationary compressor is ducting with increasing flow-area where energy transformation takes place.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] If the flow has to be turned in a rearward direction to enter the next part of the machine, e.g. another impeller or a combustor, then flow losses can be reduced by directing the flow with stationary turning vanes or individual turning pipes (pipe diffusers).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In accordance with Bernoulli's principle, the reduction in velocity causes the pressure to rise.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] While illustrating a gas turbine's Brayton cycle, Figure 5.1 includes example plots of pressure-specific volume and temperature-entropy.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] These types of plots are fundamental to understanding centrifugal compressor performance at one operating point.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The two plots show that the pressure rises between the compressor inlet (station 1) and compressor exit (station 2).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] At the same time, the specific volume decreases while the density increases.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The temperature-entropy plot shows that the temperature increases with increasing entropy (loss).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Assuming dry air, and the ideal-gas equation of state and an isentropic process, there is enough information to define the pressure ratio and efficiency for this one point.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The compressor map is required to understand the compressor performance over its complete operating range.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Figure 5.2, a centrifugal-compressor performance map (either test or estimated), shows the flow, pressure ratio for each of 4 speed-lines (total of 23 data points).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Also included are constant-efficiency contours.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Centrifugal-compressor performance presented in this form provides enough information to match the hardware represented by the map to a simple set of end-user requirements.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Compared to estimating performance, which is very cost effective (thus useful in design), testing, while costly, is still the most precise method.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Further, testing centrifugal compressor performance is very complex.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Professional societies such as ASME (i.e.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] PTC–10, Fluid Meters Handbook, PTC-19.x), ASHRAE (ASHRAE Handbook) and API (ANSI/API 617–2002, 672–2007) have established standards for detailed experimental methods and analysis of test results.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Despite this complexity, a few basic concepts in performance can be presented by examining an example test performance map.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Pressure ratio and flow are the main parameters needed to match the Figure 5.2 performance map to a simple compressor application.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In this case, it can be assumed that the inlet temperature is sea-level standard.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This assumption is not acceptable in practice, as inlet temperature variations cause significant variations in compressor performance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] As is standard practice, Figure 5.2 has a horizontal axis labeled with a flow parameter.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] While flow measurements use a variety of units, all fit one of 2 categories: mass flow per unit time or volume flow per unit time.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Mass flow units, such as kg/s, are the easiest to use in practicem, as there is little room for confusion.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Questions remaining would involve inlet or outlet (which might involve leakage from the compressor or moisture condensation).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] For atmospheric air, the mass flow may be wet or dry (including or excluding humidity).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Often, the mass-flow specification will be presented on an equivalent Mach-number basis, $m{\sqrt {\theta }}/{\delta }$ .
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] It is standard in these cases that the equivalent temperature, equivalent pressure, and gas is specified explicitly or implied at a standard condition.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In contrast, all volume-flow specifications require the additional specification of density.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Bernoulli's principle is of great value in understanding this problem.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Confusion arises through either inaccuracies or misuse of pressure, temperature, and gas constants.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Also as is standard practice, Figure 5.2 has a vertical axis labeled with a pressure parameter.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] There is a variety of pressure measurement units.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Other features common to performance maps are constant-speed lines, constant-efficiency islands, and design or guarantee points.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The two most common methods for producing a map for a centrifugal compressor are at constant shaft speed or with a constant throttle setting.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] If the speed is held constant, then test points are taken along a constant-speed line by changing throttle positions.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In contrast, if a throttle valve is held constant, then test points are established by changing speed and repeated with different throttle positions (common gas turbine practice).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The map shown in Figure 5.2 illustrates the most common method; lines of constant speed.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In this case, we see data points connected via straight lines at speeds of 50%, 71%, 87%, and 100% RPM.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The first three speed-lines have 6 points each, while the highest speed line has five.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The next feature to be discussed is the oval-shaped curves representing islands of constant efficiency.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In this figure, we see 11 contours ranging from 56% efficiency (decimal 0.56) to 76% efficiency (decimal 0.76).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] General standard practice is to interpret these efficiencies as isentropic rather than polytropic.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The inclusion of efficiency islands effectively generates a 3-dimensional topology for this 2-dimensional map.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] With inlet density specified, it provides a further ability to calculate aerodynamic power.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Lines of constant power could just as easily be substituted.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Regarding gas turbine operation and performance, there may be a series of guaranteed points established for the gas turbine's centrifugal compressor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] These requirements are of secondary importance to the overall gas turbine performance as a whole.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] For this reason, it is only necessary to summarize that in the ideal case, the lowest specific fuel consumption would occur when the centrifugal compressor's peak efficiency curve coincides with the gas turbine's required operation line.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In contrast to gas turbines, most other applications (including industrial) need to meet a less stringent set of performance requirements.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Historically, centrifugal compressors applied to industrial applications were needed to achieve performance at a specific flow and pressure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Modern industrial compressors are often needed to achieve specific performance goals across a range of flows and pressures, thus taking a significant step toward the sophistication seen in gas turbine applications.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] If the compressor represented in Figure 5.2 is used in a simple application, then any point (pressure and flow) within the 76% efficiency would provide very acceptable performance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] An end user would be very happy with the performance requirements of 2.0 pressure ratio at 0.21 kg/s.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Surge is a low-flow phenomenon where the impeller cannot add enough energy to overcome the system resistance or backpressure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] At low-flow-rate operation, the pressure ratio over the impeller is high, as is backpressure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Under critical conditions, the flow will reverse back over the tips of the rotor blades towards the impeller eye (inlet).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This stalling flow reversal may go unnoticed if the fraction of mass flow or energy is too low.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] When large enough, rapid flow reversal occurs (i.e., surge).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The reversed flow exiting the impeller inlet exhibits a strong rotational component, which affects lower-radius flow angles (closer to the impeller hub) at the leading edge of the blades.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The deterioration of the flow angles causes the impeller to be inefficient.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] (Therefore, surge is sometimes referred to as axisymmetric stall.) When reversed flow reduces to a low-enough level, the impeller recovers and regains stability for a short moment, at which point the stage may surge again.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] These cyclic events cause large vibrations, increase temperature, and change rapidly the axial thrust.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] These occurrences can damage the rotor seals, rotor bearings, the compressor driver, and cycle operation.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Most turbomachines are designed to easily withstand occasional surging.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] However, if the machine is forced to surge repeatedly for a long period of time, or if it is poorly designed, then repeated surges can result in a catastrophic failure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Of particular interest is that while turbomachines may be very durable, their physical system can be far less robust.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The surge-line shown in Figure 5.2 is the curve that passes through the lowest flow points of each of the four speed-lines.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] As a test map, these points would be the lowest flow points possible to record a stable reading within the test facility/rig.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In many industrial applications, it may be necessary to increase the stall line due to the system backpressure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] For example, at 100% RPM stalling flow might increase from approximately 0.170 kg/s to 0.215 kg/s because of the positive slope of the pressure ratio curve.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] As stated earlier, the reason for this is that the high-speed line in Figure 5.2 exhibits a stalling characteristic or positive slope within that range of flows.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] When placed in a different system, those lower flows might not be achievable because of interaction with that system.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] System resistance or adverse pressure is proven mathematically to be the critical contributor to compressor surge.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Choke occurs under one of two conditions.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Typically for high-speed equipment, as flow increases, the velocity of the flow can approach sonic speed somewhere within the compressor stage.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This location may occur at the impeller inlet "throat" or at the vaned diffuser inlet "throat".
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In contrast, for lower-speed equipment, as flows increase, losses increase such that the pressure ratio eventually drops to 1:1.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In this case, the occurrence of choke is unlikely.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The speed-lines of gas-turbine centrifugal compressors typically exhibit choke.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This is a situation where the pressure ratio of a speed line drops rapidly (vertically) with little or no change in flow.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In most cases the reason for this is that close-to-Mach-1 velocities have been reached somewhere within the impeller or diffuser, generating a rapid increase in losses.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Higher-pressure-ratio turbocharger centrifugal compressors exhibit this same phenomenon.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Real choke phenomena are a function of compressibility as measured by the local Mach number within an area restriction within the centrifugal pressure stage.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The maximum flow line, shown in Figure 5.2, is the curve that passes through the highest-flow points of each speed line.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Upon inspection, it may be noticed that each of these points has been taken near 56% efficiency.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Selecting a low efficiency (<60%) is the most common practice used to terminate compressor performance maps at high flows.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Another factor that is used to establish the maximum flow line is a pressure ratio near or equal to 1.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The 50% speed line may be considered an example of this.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The shape of Figure 5.2's speed-lines provides a good example of why it is inappropriate to use the term *choke* in association with a maximum flow of all centrifugal compressor speed-lines.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In summary, most industrial and commercial centrifugal compressors are selected or designed to operate at or near their highest efficiencies and to avoid operation at low efficiencies.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] For this reason, there is seldom a reason to illustrate centrifugal compressor performance below 60% efficiency.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Many industrial and commercial multistage compressor performance maps exhibits this same vertical characteristic for a different reason related to what is known as *stage stacking*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The minimum speed for acceptable operation; below this value, the compressor may be controlled to stop or go into an idle condition.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The maximum operating speed for the compressor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Beyond this value, stresses may rise above prescribed limits, and rotor vibrations may increase rapidly.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] At speeds above this level, the equipment will likely become very dangerous and be controlled to lower speeds.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] To weigh the advantages between centrifugal compressors, it is important to compare 8 parameters classic to turbomachinery: pressure rise (p), flow (Q), angular speed (N), power (P), density (ρ), diameter (D), viscosity (μ), and elasticity (e).
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This creates a practical problem when trying to experimentally determine the effect of any one parameter.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This is because it is nearly impossible to change one of these parameters independently.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The Buckingham π theorem can help solve this problem by generating 5 dimensionless forms of these parameters.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] These parameters provide the foundation for "similitude" and the "affinity laws" in turbomachinery.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] They provide for the creation of additional relationships (being dimensionless) found valuable in the characterization of performance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] For the example below, head will be substituted for pressure, and sonic velocity will be substituted for elasticity.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Completing the task of following the formal procedure results in generating this classic set of five dimensionless parameters for turbomachinery.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Full similitude is achieved when each one of the 5 Pi-parameters is equivalent when comparing two different cases.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This would mean the two turbomachines being compared are similar, both geometrically and in terms of performance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Turbomachinery analysts gain insight into performance by comparisons of the 5 parameters shown in the above table, especially parameters such as efficiencies and loss coefficients, which are also dimensionless.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In general applications, the flow coefficient and head coefficient are considered of primary importance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Generally, for centrifugal compressors, the speed coefficient is of secondary importance while the Reynolds coefficient is of tertiary importance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] In contrast, as expected for pumps, the Reynolds coefficient becomes of secondary importance, and the speed coefficient of tertiary importance.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] It may be found interesting that the speed coefficient may be chosen to define the y-axis of Figure 1.1, while at the same time the Reynolds coefficient may be chosen to define the z-axis.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Demonstrated in the table below is another value of dimensional analysis.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Any number of new dimensionless parameters can be calculated through exponents and multiplication.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] For example, a variation of the first parameter shown below is popularly used in aircraft-engine system analysis.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The third parameter is a simplified dimensional variation of the first and second.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This third definition is applicable with strict limitations.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The fourth parameter, specific speed, is very well-known and useful in that it removes diameter.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The fifth parameter, specific diameter, is a less-often-discussed dimensionless parameter found useful by Balje.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] It may be found interesting that the specific speed coefficient may be used in place of speed to define the y-axis of Figure 1.2, while at the same time, the specific diameter coefficient may be in place of diameter to define the z-axis.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The following *affinity laws* are derived from the five Π-parameters shown above.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] They provide a simple basis for scaling turbomachinery from one application to the next.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The following equations outline a fully three-dimensional mathematical problem that is very difficult to solve even with simplifying assumptions.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Until recently, limitations in computational power forced these equations to be simplified to an inviscid two-dimensional problem with pseudo losses.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Before the advent of computers, these equations were almost always simplified to a one-dimensional problem.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Solving this one-dimensional problem is still valuable today and is often termed *mean-line analysis*.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Even with all of this simplification, it still requires large textbooks to outline and large computer programs to solve practically.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Also termed the *Navier–Stokes equations*, this fundamental is derivable from Newton's second law when applied to fluid motion.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The first law of thermodynamics is the statement of the conservation of energy.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Under specific conditions, the operation of a centrifugal compressor is considered a reversible process.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] For a reversible process, the total amount of heat added to a system can be expressed as $\delta Q=TdS$ , where T is temperature and S is entropy.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Since U, S, and V are thermodynamic functions of state, the above relation holds also for non-reversible changes.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] The above equation is known as the fundamental thermodynamic relation.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] where $\rho$ is the density, $\gamma =C_{p}/C_{v}$ is the adiabatic index (ratio of specific heats), $U=C_{v}T$ is the internal energy per unit mass (the "specific internal energy"), $C_{v}$ is the specific heat at constant volume, and $C_{p}$ is the specific heat at constant pressure.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] For example, centrifugal compressors used for large air-conditioning systems (water chillers) use a refrigerant as a working gas that cannot be modeled as an ideal gas.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Another example is centrifugal compressors designed and built for the petroleum industry.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Most of the hydrocarbon gases, such as methane and ethylene, are best modeled with a real-gas equation of state rather than the ideal gas law.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Ideally, centrifugal compressor impellers have thin and strong airfoil blades, each mounted on a light rotor.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] This material would be easy and cheap to machine or cast.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] Additionally, it would generate no operating noise, and have a long life while operating in any environment.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] From the very start of the aero-thermodynamic design process, the aerodynamic considerations and optimizations [29,30] are critical to have a successful design.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] During the design phase, the centrifugal impeller's material and manufacturing method must be accounted for, whether it be plastic for a vacuum cleaner blower, aluminum alloy for a turbocharger, steel alloy for an air compressor, or titanium alloy for a gas turbine.
[src:centrifugal-compressor/centrifugal-compressor] It is a combination of the centrifugal-compressor impeller shape, its operating environment, its material, and its manufacturing method that determines the impeller's structural integrity.
